@DATABASE Timer
$VER: PureBasic - Timer library (05.03.2000) © Fantaisie Software
@NODE MAIN "Timer"

  @{b}PureBasic - Timer@{ub}

    This timer library is a good way to get very short but accurate
    ellapsed time between two part of your program. If you need to
    know how many time take a subroutine to be performed, this library
    is the only way. The calculated time can never be superior to one
    frame (1/50 of secs). This function is not dependent of the processor
    so the results should be the same on slow and fast Amigas.

  @{b}Commands summary:@{ub}

    @{" AllocateTimer " LINK AllocateTimer}
    @{" FreeTimer     " LINK FreeTimer}
    @{" InitTimer     " LINK InitTimer}
    @{" StartTimer    " LINK StartTimer}
    @{" StopTimer     " LINK StopTimer}

    @{" Timer Demo    " LINK PureBasic:Examples/Sources/Timer.pb/Main}
@ENDNODE


@Node AllocateTimer

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  @{b}Result@{ub}.b = AllocateTimer()

    @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
  This function try to allocate one CIA timer.

  Don't call it more than once without a call to
  FreeTimer() in between.

  @{b}Result@{ub}
  TRUE if a timer is allocated else FALSE.

@EndNode


@Node FreeTimer

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  FreeTimer()

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  To free the CIA timer which is allocated with
  AllocateTimer(), then call this statement.

@EndNode


@Node InitTimer

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  InitTimer()

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  Always call this statement befor any other routines
  in Timer Lib.

@EndNode


@Node StartTimer

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  StartTimer()

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  This statement start the timer.

@EndNode


@Node StopTimer

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  @{b}Result@{ub}.w = StopTimer()

    @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
  This function stop the timer.

  @{b}Result@{ub}
  If this is -1 then the time taken is greater or
  equal to the time of one frame. That mean it is
  out of range for the timeing purpose done by
  Timer Lib. If it instead is a positive value it
  should be multiplyed with 1.39 to convert it to
  microseconds.

@EndNode

